{"title_page": "Feast of Saint Mark", "text_new": "The '''Feast of Saint Mark''' commemorates [[Mark the Evangelist]] and takes place on April 25. \n\n==Local observances and customs==\n\n===Italy===\nThe 25th of April is national holiday throughout Italy, though not as Saint Mark's Day, but as [[Liberation Day (Italy)|anniversary of the liberation of Italy]] from the Nazi-Fascists in World War II (25 April 1945).  It is also believed to have been the date that vampires were eradicated from  Italy and some homes also celebrate this event. Celebrations can also be seen in media - \nthe Twilight Movie Saga : New Moon. \n\n====Sardinia====\nIn [[Tresnuraghes]], a small village in [[Sardinia]] ([[Italy]]), a traditional Sardinian feast is held. Local [[shepherd]] families in this predominantly pastoral community offer sheep and oversee cooking them in a gesture of thanks to [[Divine providence|Providence]]. Other families offer bread as [[thanksgiving]] or for favors desired.  Hundreds of people, mostly from said village, but a large number of other people as well, eat and drink to satiation together.<ref>Counihan, Carole.  The Anthropology of Food and Body. Page 39.</ref>\n\n==== Venice ====\n[[File:La tradizione del dono del \"Bocol\".jpg|thumb|''Festa del boco\u0142o'' ([[rose]]bud festival) in [[Piazza San Marco|St Mark's Square]], Venice]]\nThe Feast of Saint Mark ({{lang-it|Festa di san Marco}}), also known as the rosebud festival ([[Venetian language|Venetian]]: ''festa del b\u00f3co\u0142o''), is a festival in [[Venice]] held on 25 April celebrating Venice's [[patron saint]], [[Saint Mark]]. On this day, men traditionally give a single [[rose bud|rosebud]] to the women they love.<ref>Bing, Alison. [https://books.google.com/books?id=W8t9KPwqva8C&pg=PA18&dq=Festa+Del+bocolo&hl=en&ei=elsHTd6kF4P78Ab48NTpAg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=9&ved=0CEwQ6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=Festa%20Del%20bocolo&f=false \"Venice & the Veneto\"], 2010.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.veneziasi.it/it/tradizioni-venezia/festa-san-marco.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-12-12 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304084636/http://www.veneziasi.it/it/tradizioni-venezia/festa-san-marco.html |archive-date=2016-03-04 |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"Venezia\">Touring Club Italiano. [https://books.google.com/books?id=ZlqudfwX2xIC&pg=PA110&dq=Festa+Del+bocolo&hl=en&ei=elsHTd6kF4P78Ab48NTpAg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=Festa%20Del%20bocolo&f=false \"Guida d'Italia, Venezia\"], 1985.</ref>\n\nAccording to legend, the tradition originated in the 8th century, when a man of low social standing is said to have fallen in love with a noblewoman from Venice. In order to win her father's approval, he became involved in a distant war. He was mortally wounded in battle, but managed to pluck a rose from a nearby rosebush for his loved one. A companion was entrusted with returning the blood-stained rose to his lover.<ref name=\"Venezia\"/><ref>http://veniceblog.typepad.com/veniceblog/2004/04/the_legend_of_t.html</ref><ref>http://www.ombra.net/tradizione/festa-san-marco/index.php</ref>\n\n===Lithuania===\nIn Lithuania, St. Mark is considered the guardian of earth and harvests. There was a ban on eating meat in order to have a good harvest. People avoided \"touching the earth\", i.e. no plowing or digging, to give the earth a rest before the upcoming hard work of planting and harvest.<ref>[http://ausis.gf.vu.lt/eka/customs/mark.html Lithuanian Customs and Traditions] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205044511/http://ausis.gf.vu.lt/eka/customs/mark.html |date=2008-12-05 }}</ref>\n\n===Mexico===\nThis festivity is celebrated in the city of [[Aguascalientes City|Aguascalientes]], Mexico on the same date. It gives name to one of the most celebrated festivities, the Saint Mark National Fair (Spanish: [[Feria Nacional de San Marcos]]) which runs generally for three weeks around this date.\n\nAlso, in [[Para\u00edso, Tabasco]], Mexico, Saint Mark is celebrated the 25 April due to his patronage of that city.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Saint Mark's Eve]]\n* [[Calendar of saints]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mark}}\n[[Category:Saints days]]\n[[Category:April observances]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Feast of Saint Mark''' commemorates [[Mark the Evangelist]] and takes place on April 25. \n\n==Local observances and customs==\n\n===Italy===\nThe 25th of April is national holiday throughout Italy, though not as Saint Mark's Day, but as [[Liberation Day (Italy)|anniversary of the liberation of Italy]] from the Nazi-Fascists in World War II (25 April 1945).  It is also believed to have been the date that vampires were eradicated from  Italy and some homes also celebrate this event. Celebrations can also be seen in media - \nthe Twilight Movie Saga : New Moon. \n\n====Sardinia====\nIn [[Tresnuraghes]], a small village in [[Sardinia]] ([[Italy]]), a traditional Sardinian feast is held. Local [[shepherd]] families in this predominantly pastoral community offer sheep and oversee cooking them in a gesture of thanks to [[Divine providence|Providence]]. Other families offer bread as [[thanksgiving]] or for favors desired.  Hundreds of people, mostly from said village, but a large number of other people as well, eat and drink to satiation together.<ref>Counihan, Carole.  The Anthropology of Food and Body. Page 39.</ref>\n\n==== Venice ====\n[[File:La tradizione del dono del \"Bocol\".jpg|thumb|''Festa del boco\u0142o'' ([[rose]]bud festival) in [[Piazza San Marco|St Mark's Square]], Venice]]\nThe Feast of Saint Mark ({{lang-it|Festa di san Marco}}), also known as the rosebud festival ([[Venetian language|Venetian]]: ''festa del b\u00f3co\u0142o''), is a festival in [[Venice]] held on 25 April celebrating Venice's [[patron saint]], [[Saint Mark]]. On this day, men traditionally give a single [[rose bud|rosebud]] to the women they love.<ref>Bing, Alison. [https://books.google.com/books?id=W8t9KPwqva8C&pg=PA18&dq=Festa+Del+bocolo&hl=en&ei=elsHTd6kF4P78Ab48NTpAg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=9&ved=0CEwQ6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=Festa%20Del%20bocolo&f=false \"Venice & the Veneto\"], 2010.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.veneziasi.it/it/tradizioni-venezia/festa-san-marco.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-12-12 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304084636/http://www.veneziasi.it/it/tradizioni-venezia/festa-san-marco.html |archive-date=2016-03-04 |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"Venezia\">Touring Club Italiano. [https://books.google.com/books?id=ZlqudfwX2xIC&pg=PA110&dq=Festa+Del+bocolo&hl=en&ei=elsHTd6kF4P78Ab48NTpAg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=Festa%20Del%20bocolo&f=false \"Guida d'Italia, Venezia\"], 1985.</ref>\n\nAccording to legend, the tradition originated in the 8th century, when a man of low social standing is said to have fallen in love with a noblewoman from Venice. In order to win her father's approval, he became involved in a distant war. He was mortally wounded in battle, but managed to pluck a rose from a nearby rosebush for his loved one. A companion was entrusted with returning the blood-stained rose to his lover.<ref name=\"Venezia\"/><ref>http://veniceblog.typepad.com/veniceblog/2004/04/the_legend_of_t.html</ref><ref>http://www.ombra.net/tradizione/festa-san-marco/index.php</ref>\n\n===Lithuania===\nIn Lithuania, St. Mark is considered the guardian of earth and harvests. There was a ban on eating meat in order to have a good harvest. People avoided \"touching the earth\", i.e. no plowing or digging, to give the earth a rest before the upcoming hard work of planting and harvest.<ref>[http://ausis.gf.vu.lt/eka/customs/mark.html Lithuanian Customs and Traditions] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205044511/http://ausis.gf.vu.lt/eka/customs/mark.html |date=2008-12-05 }}</ref>\n\n===Mexico===\nThis festivity is celebrated in the city of [[Aguascalientes City|Aguascalientes]], Mexico on the same date. It gives name to one of the most celebrated festivities, the Saint Mark National Fair (Spanish: [[Feria Nacional de San Marcos]]) which runs generally for three weeks around this date.\n\nAlso, in [[Para\u00edso, Tabasco]], Mexico, Saint Mark is celebrated the 25 April due to his patronage of that city.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Saint Mark's Eve]]\n* [[Saints days]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mark}}\n[[Category:Saints days]]\n[[Category:April observances]]\n", "name_user": "PFHLai", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also:avoid redirect toCalendar of saints", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Feast_of_Saint_Mark"}
